            "id": "4748905",
            "title": "Gaztransport & Technigaz: Recent Developments Strenghtens Our Investment Thesis",
            "description": "<p>Gaztransport &amp; Technigaz (<span>GTT) (<a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/symbol/GZPZF\" title=\"Gaztransport &amp; Technigaz SA\" target=\"_blank\">OTCPK:GZPZF</a>) has performed very well and significantly outperformed European equity markets since our last</span><a href=\"https://seekingalpha.com/article/4598019-gtt-high-quality-very-profitable-structurally-growing-immune-to-short-term-economic-conditions\" title=\"https://seekingalpha.com/article/4598019-gtt-high-quality-very-profitable-structurally-growing-immune-to-short-term-economic-conditions\" target=\"_blank\"> <span>article</span></a><span>. Since then, the total shareholder return has reached +57% (in euros), versus +17% for the broad equity index EuroStoxx 600. As a reminder, GTT is the global leader in the cryogenic membrane technology used for LNG transport and storage. With a robust order backlog in a monopoly market, the company is well-positioned to deliver strong financial results until the end of the decade. The business should keep growing thanks to an increasing LNG demand, an aging vessel fleet, and stricter environmental regulations. Additionally, the adoption of LNG as a fuel, driven by its cost-effectiveness and widespread availability, should also support the growth profile, particularly as more containerships transition to this solution.</span></p> <p><span>We continue to believe that the stock offers a compelling investment opportunity given recent developments and a lacklustre 2024 performance of only </span>~<span>13%. GTT was somewhat penalized by all political noises around the French assembly dissolution and budget discussion, especially the ones considering new and/or higher taxes on corporates. However, this higher potential tax rate (if voted) may not impact the company, in our view. Indeed, royalties, which account for</span>~ <span>90% of total revenue, are taxed at 10% according to the French tax regulation. This preferential tax rate results from the</span><a href=\"https://taxsummaries.pwc.com/france/corporate/tax-credits-and-incentives\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"https://taxsummaries.pwc.com/france/corporate/tax-credits-and-incentives\" target=\"_blank\"> <span>patent box regulation</span></a><span>, which enables IP-based income to be taxed at a reduced rate (instead of the current standard rate of 25%). Therefore, if the government decides to increase the statutory tax rate, it should not impact the company given that 90% of its revenue are not subject to this taxation and the remaining 10% of sales are loss-making. The only possible negative scenario could result from a</span><a href=\"https://www.senat.fr/amendements/2024-2025/143/Amdt_I-1254.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"https://www.senat.fr/amendements/2024-2025/143/Amdt_I-1254.html\" target=\"_blank\"> <span>patent box regulation change,</span></a><span> increasing the</span></p>",
            "image": null,
            "link": "https://seekingalpha.com/article/4748905-gaztransport-and-technigaz-recent-developments-strenghtens-our-investment-thesis",
            "pub_date": "2025-01-11 21:30:21",
